WEBVTT

00:01.041 --> 00:08.125
♪

00:08.125 --> 00:09.083
GREG: All right,
keep ’em closed.

00:09.083 --> 00:10.291
JEN: Yup, they’re closed.
GREG: They’re closed?

00:10.291 --> 00:11.750
JEN: Yes, okay.
GREG: All right.

00:11.750 --> 00:13.875
Okay, you ready for your
Valentine’s Day surprise?

00:13.875 --> 00:15.625
Yeah, it’s gonna be tough
to beat all our other

00:15.625 --> 00:17.166
Valentine’s Day surprises,

00:17.166 --> 00:19.583
the flu, our basement flooding,

00:19.583 --> 00:20.917
the time that
you got pepper sprayed

00:20.917 --> 00:23.250
-by that lady selling roses.
-Yeah, I was just reaching

00:23.250 --> 00:25.333
for a hair, I didn’t know
it was attached to her face.

00:25.333 --> 00:27.333
-Okay, open your eyes.
-Okay.

00:27.333 --> 00:29.000
Ah, oh my God!

00:29.000 --> 00:32.041
Greg, this is so romantic!

00:32.041 --> 00:33.709
Happy Valentine’s Day!

00:33.709 --> 00:36.959
Tonight we break the tradition
of horrible Valentine’s Days.

00:36.959 --> 00:39.834
That means we are stayin’ in,
no traffic,

00:39.834 --> 00:41.458
right, no goin’ to
the wrong restaurant,

00:41.458 --> 00:43.291
no bathroom
accidents in traffic

00:43.291 --> 00:44.625
on the way to
the wrong restaurant.

00:44.625 --> 00:45.959
Yeah, well, I was pregnant.

00:45.959 --> 00:47.250
It happens to a lot of women.

00:47.250 --> 00:49.166
We’ve got a private chef

00:49.166 --> 00:51.166
who’s cooking us
a very romantic dinner.

00:51.166 --> 00:54.959
So tonight,
the restaurant is right here.

00:54.959 --> 00:56.458
Allie: Hello.
JEN: Oh, hi!

00:56.458 --> 00:59.083
-Hi, I’m Allie, you must be Jen.
-Hi.

00:59.083 --> 01:00.125
I am.

01:00.125 --> 01:02.125
ALLIE: Hope you guys are hungry.

01:02.125 --> 01:04.667
JEN: Wow, that looks amazing!

01:04.667 --> 01:05.792
No, you look amazing.

01:05.792 --> 01:08.041
-Thank you.
-Your body’s so tight.

01:08.041 --> 01:09.458
ALLIE: A little vino.
GREG: Yeah, sure.

01:09.458 --> 01:10.834
Fill it to the top!

01:10.834 --> 01:12.208
We ain’t got nowhere to drive,

01:12.208 --> 01:14.667
and the baby’s with
the sitter until tomorrow.

01:14.667 --> 01:16.542
ALLIE: Aw, you guys have a baby?

01:16.542 --> 01:18.250
GREG: Yeah.
-Fun.

01:18.250 --> 01:20.125
The state has my baby.

01:20.125 --> 01:21.333
Enjoy the crab salad.

01:23.458 --> 01:25.000
-Huh.
-Well, honey,

01:25.000 --> 01:26.583
this really, it means so much.

01:26.583 --> 01:28.375
I know that you would have
preferred to spend the money

01:28.375 --> 01:30.583
-on a close-up magic guy.
-No, no, no, baby,

01:30.583 --> 01:32.000
tonight is all about you.

01:32.000 --> 01:33.458
I mean, Heather gave
me the recommendation

01:33.458 --> 01:35.250
for Allie here, so I booked her.

01:35.250 --> 01:37.500
-Aw.
-Besides, Eric the Amazing

01:37.500 --> 01:38.917
was not available.

01:38.917 --> 01:40.041
But don’t worry!

01:40.041 --> 01:43.041
I already locked him down
for Christmas Eve 2018.

01:43.041 --> 01:46.041
Well, if this food tastes
as good as it looks,

01:46.041 --> 01:48.542
that’s not the only thing
you’re gonna have locked down.

01:48.542 --> 01:51.291
-That’s what I’m talkin’ about.
-Okay, hey-oh!

01:51.291 --> 01:54.917
Also, I’m gonna be out of town
for Christmas Eve 2018.

01:54.917 --> 01:56.166
♪

01:56.166 --> 01:57.500
I just remembered.

01:57.500 --> 02:00.583
♪

02:00.583 --> 02:02.792
-Who’s ready for round two?
JEN: Mm!

02:02.792 --> 02:04.667
-Hey, hey!
JEN: Oh!

02:04.667 --> 02:06.417
This is the best meal I have had

02:06.417 --> 02:08.208
since we took that
trip to New Orleans.

02:08.208 --> 02:09.583
JEN: I remember that!

02:09.583 --> 02:11.709
Yeah, that was the trip
where you decided to march

02:11.709 --> 02:12.875
with everyone’s funerals.

02:12.875 --> 02:14.000
Yeah, they’re
called second lines.

02:14.000 --> 02:16.208
JEN: Yeah.
-I remember when I had love.

02:16.208 --> 02:18.041
(laughing)

02:18.041 --> 02:19.625
ALLIE: Long time ago!

02:19.625 --> 02:21.667
My ex-husband was
a gambling addict.

02:21.667 --> 02:23.792
I bet he still is,
unless he’s dead.

02:23.792 --> 02:25.083
Wouldn’t that be weird?

02:25.083 --> 02:26.291
That’d be so weird.

02:26.291 --> 02:28.166
(wine pouring)

02:28.166 --> 02:30.583
-Cheers!
JEN: Cheers.

02:31.917 --> 02:32.917
(stomping)

02:32.917 --> 02:34.875
Y’all gotta get this fixed,
it’s broken.

02:37.375 --> 02:38.834
Hey, do you think
she should be drinking

02:38.834 --> 02:41.875
that much wine with, ya know,
knives and a hot stove,

02:41.875 --> 02:43.542
and the emergency cash
you keep in that box

02:43.542 --> 02:44.875
of ice cream sandwiches?

02:44.875 --> 02:48.041
No--She’s fine, I mean,
she’s a professional.

02:48.041 --> 02:48.959
Okay.

02:48.959 --> 02:50.166
(glass breaking)

02:50.166 --> 02:53.917
ALLIE: Who keeps glass
in a kitchen?

02:53.917 --> 02:55.417
But on second thought...

02:55.417 --> 02:58.291
Yeah, probably a good idea.

02:58.291 --> 03:00.041
(humming)

03:01.917 --> 03:03.125
GREG: Allie?

03:03.125 --> 03:04.166
Everything okay?

03:04.166 --> 03:06.208
Oh, it’s so great,
everything’s fine.

03:06.208 --> 03:08.667
Who’s ready for the main course?

03:08.667 --> 03:10.458
Damn it, Allie!

03:10.458 --> 03:11.625
You’re a mess up here,

03:11.625 --> 03:13.417
you’re a mess down there.

03:13.417 --> 03:14.500
I’m so sorry.

03:14.500 --> 03:16.208
-It’s okay.
-Are you mad at me?

03:16.208 --> 03:18.750
No, I’m not mad at you.

03:18.750 --> 03:21.000
-Are you mad at me?
-No, I’m not.

03:21.000 --> 03:23.458
(food bubbling)

03:23.458 --> 03:24.917
-Confused, but I’m not mad.
-You mad at me?

03:24.917 --> 03:26.500
No, I’m not mad.

03:26.500 --> 03:27.500
Everything’s fine.

03:27.500 --> 03:28.583
Are you enjoying your meal?

03:28.583 --> 03:30.125
Yes, I am enjoying the meal.

03:30.125 --> 03:31.667
It’s the best
Valentine’s Day ever,

03:31.667 --> 03:33.625
so I’m gonna really need you
to focus, you know,

03:33.625 --> 03:35.834
and, and, and just keep it up.

03:35.834 --> 03:37.834
Isn’t that what I
should be saying to you?

03:37.834 --> 03:41.000
-Huh?
-Um...no.

03:41.000 --> 03:42.041
-Huh?
-No!

03:42.041 --> 03:43.375
JEN: Oops, oops,
oops, oops, oops!

03:43.375 --> 03:45.709
-Thank God.
-Hi, and then I arrive.

03:45.709 --> 03:47.083
ALLIE: Oh here, have a meat.

03:47.083 --> 03:48.625
JEN: Oh, my God, wow!

03:48.625 --> 03:50.709
(sarcastic laughing)

03:50.709 --> 03:53.208
Is that my medical ID bracelet?

03:53.208 --> 03:54.583
I don’t know, maybe it is.

03:54.583 --> 03:56.041
Did I find it in the bathroom
and think it was cool,

03:56.041 --> 03:57.000
and put it on?

03:57.000 --> 03:58.250
Maybe, maybe not.

03:58.250 --> 04:01.542
(sarcastic laughing)

04:01.542 --> 04:04.417
JEN: So, on a,
on a scale of one to ten,

04:04.417 --> 04:06.500
how certain are you that she has

04:06.500 --> 04:08.166
no criminal record?

04:08.166 --> 04:10.500
(utensils clanging)

04:10.500 --> 04:11.875
Let’s just keep an open mind.

04:11.875 --> 04:13.417
-Yeah, okay.
-Right, okay.

04:13.417 --> 04:14.583
GREG: In the meantime though,

04:14.583 --> 04:17.500
I am definitely going
to go do a quick inventory

04:17.500 --> 04:20.375
of all of my priceless
<i>Star Wars </i>figurines.

04:20.375 --> 04:22.417
What?

04:22.417 --> 04:23.583
JEN: Uh, Allie,

04:23.583 --> 04:25.959
could I just talk to you
for just a hot minute?

04:25.959 --> 04:27.709
Thank you so much.

04:27.709 --> 04:30.208
So, this, first of all, looks...

04:30.208 --> 04:32.875
A+, but you know,
I don’t wanna eat too much

04:32.875 --> 04:35.583
just ’cause I have to
slip into lingerie later,

04:35.583 --> 04:37.208
and so I was
thinkin’ I could just

04:37.208 --> 04:38.583
put you in a cab,
send you home.

04:38.583 --> 04:39.959
You can have a nice night.

04:39.959 --> 04:43.000
Oh, I get it,
I know what you’re thinking.

04:43.000 --> 04:46.083
That you smell like
literally all of my perfumes.

04:46.083 --> 04:49.250
That your man’s gonna
slip out of your fingertips

04:49.250 --> 04:51.709
and into mine, but don’t worry.

04:51.709 --> 04:55.041
These goods aren’t on the menu.

04:57.166 --> 04:58.417
♪

04:58.417 --> 05:01.250
(phone trilling)

05:01.250 --> 05:04.000
Hey, what’s go--Oh, no.
Is the food not good?

05:04.000 --> 05:05.917
No, no, the food is delicious.

05:05.917 --> 05:07.458
It’s just Allie is wasted.

05:07.458 --> 05:11.500
Oh, shoot, she was in such
a good place six months ago!

05:11.500 --> 05:14.250
-She’d just gotten out of rehab.
-Wait, she was in rehab?

05:14.250 --> 05:16.125
HEATHER:<i> Yeah, her husband</i>
<i>left her at a truck stop,</i>

05:16.125 --> 05:17.333
where she became a prostitute.

05:17.333 --> 05:18.959
<i>You know,</i>
<i>she’s had some problems.</i>

05:18.959 --> 05:20.917
<i>Hey, would you call me</i>

05:20.917 --> 05:23.166
if Allie starts snorting
the baking powder?

05:23.166 --> 05:24.750
Yeah, okay, thank you.

05:24.750 --> 05:27.291
♪

05:27.291 --> 05:28.583
Okay, well...

05:28.583 --> 05:29.875
Looks like we’re just gonna

05:29.875 --> 05:31.458
jump ahead to dessert.

05:31.458 --> 05:32.625
I’m predicting
that’s gonna be our

05:32.625 --> 05:34.417
salt and pepper shakers
dipped in chocolate.

05:34.417 --> 05:35.458
Oh, come on.

05:35.458 --> 05:38.500
I am so sorry, all right.

05:38.500 --> 05:42.250
All I wanted was just
one good Valentine’s Day.

05:42.250 --> 05:44.583
And, we had one.

05:44.583 --> 05:45.959
It was perfect.

05:45.959 --> 05:48.417
Honestly, all of our
Valentine’s have been perfect.

05:48.417 --> 05:50.583
I mean, they’ve been
total disasters,

05:50.583 --> 05:53.250
but they’ve been our disasters.

05:53.250 --> 05:55.875
And I wouldn’t have them
any other way.

05:55.875 --> 05:58.208
Me neither.

05:58.208 --> 06:00.917
(glass shattering)

06:00.917 --> 06:02.291
JEN: Oh, my God.

06:02.291 --> 06:04.709
(groaning)

06:05.917 --> 06:08.875
ALLIE: Oh, oh.

06:08.875 --> 06:10.792
Would either of you
like dessert?

06:10.792 --> 06:15.375
♪

06:15.375 --> 06:19.792
COLLEEN: Ah, look at this
sweet three-legged girl!

06:19.792 --> 06:22.208
Think that means
something else, and also...

06:22.208 --> 06:23.458
that’s a boy.

06:23.458 --> 06:25.875
Oh, look how sweet he is!

06:25.875 --> 06:28.291
MATT: Yeah.
-His bandana says "Soul Mate."

06:28.291 --> 06:29.458
Maybe we should adopt him.

06:29.458 --> 06:31.208
Well, Princess does
need a new friend.

06:31.208 --> 06:32.792
He’s humped his
stuffed bear so much

06:32.792 --> 06:34.291
it’s become a finger puppet.

06:34.291 --> 06:36.625
This would be our first
big purchase as a couple.

06:36.625 --> 06:38.166
And it’s free,
which is even better.

06:38.166 --> 06:40.625
-Yeah.
RUTH: Well, the bandana is $5.

06:40.625 --> 06:43.250
-But we don’t wanna spoil him.
-Yeah.

06:43.250 --> 06:44.375
Are we gonna do this?

06:47.000 --> 06:49.417
We’ll take him.

06:49.417 --> 06:51.375
This totally replaces
the memory of my dad

06:51.375 --> 06:53.041
leaving us on Valentine’s Day.

06:53.041 --> 06:55.291
MATT: Oh, no pressure.

06:55.291 --> 06:56.750
♪

06:56.750 --> 06:58.875
Thank you for starting
the adoption journey.

06:58.875 --> 07:01.375
MATT: Yeah.
RUTH: It’s a four-week process

07:01.375 --> 07:03.250
with several in-home visits.

07:03.250 --> 07:05.041
Shall we em-bark?

07:05.041 --> 07:06.750
Ha!

07:06.750 --> 07:08.000
It’s okay to laugh.

07:08.000 --> 07:09.041
(laughing)

07:09.041 --> 07:10.291
MATT: At?
RUTH: All right,

07:10.291 --> 07:13.000
so this is a release
so we can run your credit.

07:13.000 --> 07:15.333
Oh, we’re not
getting the bandana.

07:15.333 --> 07:18.125
I know, but we need to know if
you can financially support him

07:18.125 --> 07:20.250
and give him
everything he deserves.

07:20.250 --> 07:22.500
Okay, but you know,
just to be clear,

07:22.500 --> 07:25.083
he has three legs, and if he
doesn’t get adopted, he dies.

07:25.083 --> 07:26.917
RUTH: Well, some fates
are worse than death.

07:26.917 --> 07:28.583
-Are they, ’cause, uh--
-You know, we’ll do

07:28.583 --> 07:29.917
whatever it takes.

07:29.917 --> 07:32.375
You are gonna be
part of our family!

07:32.375 --> 07:33.500
We’ll see.

07:33.500 --> 07:34.583
And, until it’s official,

07:34.583 --> 07:36.875
can you please communicate
with the dog through me?

07:38.959 --> 07:40.208
Okay.

07:40.208 --> 07:42.291
Was that to me, or the dog?

07:42.291 --> 07:44.125
’Cause you had one eye
that went.

07:44.125 --> 07:46.041
-I know, I have a lazy eye.
-It’s just--she has a lazy eye.

07:46.041 --> 07:47.750
I have to write this down.

07:47.750 --> 07:49.917
♪

07:49.917 --> 07:52.250
COLLEEN: And Princess
sleeps in the bed with us.

07:52.250 --> 07:54.125
Well, we sleep in Princess’ bed.

07:54.125 --> 07:55.709
(laughing)

07:55.709 --> 07:56.959
MATT: I don’t even need
an alarm clock.

07:56.959 --> 07:58.333
I’ve got Princess’ tongue.

07:58.333 --> 08:00.667
(laughing)

08:00.667 --> 08:02.000
But we don’t

08:02.000 --> 08:03.500
make love with
the dog in the room.

08:03.500 --> 08:04.834
Obviously, we don’t think
that’s appropriate.

08:04.834 --> 08:06.417
No, no.

08:06.417 --> 08:08.333
-Our toilet water’s filtered.
-Oh, yeah.

08:08.333 --> 08:09.417
-Okay.
COLLEEN: Yeah.

08:09.417 --> 08:12.625
And we have great schools
in this neighborhood.

08:12.625 --> 08:14.208
Also we have had sex
in front of Princess.

08:14.208 --> 08:15.208
I don’t know why I said that.

08:15.208 --> 08:16.709
I don’t wanna
start out with a lie.

08:16.709 --> 08:18.458
Well, you have a lovely home.

08:18.458 --> 08:19.583
-Oh, thank you.
RUTH: But,

08:19.583 --> 08:20.875
I’m afraid it’s a no.

08:20.875 --> 08:22.083
Why, is this because I lied?

08:22.083 --> 08:24.542
Matt lied too, he definitely
has an alarm clock.

08:24.542 --> 08:26.625
I don’t think you’re
gonna make it as a couple.

08:26.625 --> 08:27.917
You know,
it’s just a gut feeling.

08:27.917 --> 08:30.000
I’m very good at
judging relationships,

08:30.000 --> 08:33.041
except my own
’cause my life is a disaster.

08:33.041 --> 08:36.250
Anyway, it was really
nice to meet you guys!

08:36.250 --> 08:37.750
♪

08:37.750 --> 08:39.166
MATT: You really sure
you wanna do this?

08:39.166 --> 08:40.417
We could just adopt
a different dog.

08:40.417 --> 08:41.667
It’s not just about the dog.

08:41.667 --> 08:43.166
It’s about someone questioning

08:43.166 --> 08:46.583
-the strength of our love.
-Right, right.

08:46.583 --> 08:47.542
Excuse me.

08:47.542 --> 08:48.834
Okay.

08:48.834 --> 08:50.792
That’s a good girl.

08:50.792 --> 08:52.083
-Whoa!
-Oh!

08:52.083 --> 08:54.083
Hey, got a little--

08:54.083 --> 08:55.291
I gotta what?

08:55.291 --> 08:57.375
MATT: You got a little
bite there?

08:57.375 --> 08:59.417
Yes, ferret.

08:59.417 --> 09:00.333
Okay.

09:00.333 --> 09:01.250
Well, you might remember us.

09:01.250 --> 09:03.000
We are the people that you
thought weren’t good enough

09:03.000 --> 09:04.792
for one of your
almost dead dogs,

09:04.792 --> 09:06.375
and we’re back
because we don’t give up.

09:06.375 --> 09:08.583
MATT: No, and also because
we can’t afford a purebred.

09:08.583 --> 09:10.959
But, also mostly because
we don’t give up.

09:10.959 --> 09:12.959
COLLEEN: And we thought about
giving up for a couple days.

09:12.959 --> 09:15.417
Yeah, after you left, we
thought, "What’s wrong with us?"

09:15.417 --> 09:16.875
And then we started
listing each others’ faults,

09:16.875 --> 09:19.709
-which really got ugly.
-So dark.

09:19.709 --> 09:21.542
But after yesterday,
we got back together again.

09:21.542 --> 09:22.875
RUTH: Oh!
-And we realized

09:22.875 --> 09:23.959
that we are
meant to be together,

09:23.959 --> 09:25.000
and we are meant
to have this dog,

09:25.000 --> 09:26.834
and if you can’t
see that, then maybe,

09:26.834 --> 09:28.208
maybe this dog just,
I don’t know,

09:28.208 --> 09:29.250
-isn’t even worth it!
-Nope!

09:29.250 --> 09:31.041
Got away from you
there at the end.

09:31.041 --> 09:32.250
-She knows what I’m saying.
-Okay.

09:32.250 --> 09:34.458
I do, and that’s exactly
the fighting spirit

09:34.458 --> 09:35.583
I was hoping for!

09:35.583 --> 09:37.125
-Oh.
RUTH: Let’s reopen the file.

09:37.125 --> 09:38.792
COLLEEN: Okay.
RUTH: Okay, sit!

09:38.792 --> 09:41.250
MATT: Okay.
COLLEEN: Okay, here we go.

09:41.250 --> 09:43.750
Over here, sit over here.

09:43.750 --> 09:44.875
Come!

09:44.875 --> 09:46.792
♪

09:46.792 --> 09:48.500
This dog

09:48.500 --> 09:50.208
is a symbol of our love.

09:50.208 --> 09:51.667
We’re stronger
when we’re challenged.

09:51.667 --> 09:52.834
-We are.
-Mm-hmm.

09:52.834 --> 09:54.000
This is gonna happen in life.

09:54.000 --> 09:55.083
People are gonna front,

09:55.083 --> 09:56.625
and we’re gonna step to it!

09:56.625 --> 09:58.917
-What?
-Okay, okay.

09:58.917 --> 10:00.000
Maybe we don’t do that
in front of the dog

10:00.000 --> 10:01.291
’cause you know
you’re gonna scare him,

10:01.291 --> 10:02.792
right, but you’re right!

10:02.792 --> 10:04.917
Buttons is very
lucky to have us!

10:04.917 --> 10:06.125
Isn’t that right, Buttons?

10:08.583 --> 10:09.875
COLLEEN: Buttons?

10:09.875 --> 10:11.000
Oh, Buttons!

10:11.000 --> 10:12.041
Ya scared him.

10:12.041 --> 10:13.417
His name is Buttons, right?

10:13.417 --> 10:14.792
MATT: I think so.
COLLEEN: Buttons?

10:14.792 --> 10:16.583
COLLEEN: Buttons?
MATT: Buttons?

10:16.583 --> 10:18.542
COLLEEN: Buttons, come on, boy!
MATT: Buttons!

10:18.542 --> 10:19.750
I can’t believe
we let this happen.

10:19.750 --> 10:21.583
I know, we have to find him.

10:21.583 --> 10:23.417
I miss his little black fur.

10:23.417 --> 10:25.500
Well, he’s brown, I think.

10:25.500 --> 10:26.834
Oh, I didn’t get a good look.

10:26.834 --> 10:30.375
-I love him so much, Buttons!
-Buttons!

10:30.375 --> 10:32.834
(phone ringing)

10:32.834 --> 10:34.250
-Hello?
<i>RUTH: Mr. Short,</i>

10:34.250 --> 10:37.000
<i>Ruth Puxtus-Silverstein</i>
<i>from the adoption fair.</i>

10:37.000 --> 10:38.959
Oh, hi, Ruth!

10:38.959 --> 10:41.291
Hi, I’m just doing my
doggie due diligence

10:41.291 --> 10:42.291
and checking in.

10:42.291 --> 10:43.792
<i>How’s it</i>
<i>going with Buttons?</i>

10:43.792 --> 10:45.083
Oh, it’s so great, we love him!

10:45.083 --> 10:48.583
Yeah, he is just the cutest
little to medium-sized thing!

10:48.583 --> 10:50.792
Oh, look how cute his is
when he does that little thing!

10:50.792 --> 10:52.125
<i>MATT: Oh, yes he does,</i>
<i>yes he does.</i>

10:52.125 --> 10:54.542
That is so surprising

10:54.542 --> 10:57.125
because he’s sitting
right here next to me.

10:57.125 --> 10:59.750
Yeah, little guy ran across
an eight-lane freeway

10:59.750 --> 11:01.625
<i>to find his way back here.</i>

11:01.625 --> 11:03.458
Then, then, then,
which Buttons is this?

11:03.458 --> 11:05.417
Get outta here,
you filthy animal!

11:05.417 --> 11:06.917
<i>MATT: Sorry, you know what--</i>
<i>COLLEEN: Sorry!</i>

11:06.917 --> 11:08.166
We’ll come right down.

11:08.166 --> 11:09.834
We’ll straighten
all of this out.

11:09.834 --> 11:11.500
No, stay!

11:11.500 --> 11:12.625
<i>Stay!</i>

11:12.625 --> 11:14.834
♪

11:14.834 --> 11:17.542
COLLEEN: Oh,
what if Ruth is right?

11:17.542 --> 11:19.041
What if there’s
some weakness in us

11:19.041 --> 11:21.375
that only she
and dogs can sense?

11:21.375 --> 11:22.333
There’s not!

11:22.333 --> 11:23.583
We made a mistake.

11:23.583 --> 11:25.333
You know,
and whenever we make them,

11:25.333 --> 11:26.417
we learn from them,

11:26.417 --> 11:27.583
and we grow stronger...

11:27.583 --> 11:28.709
-Yes.
-...and we get better.

11:28.709 --> 11:30.166
We’re like a super germ.

11:30.166 --> 11:33.083
-You are so romantic.
-I know.

11:33.083 --> 11:34.667
(giggling)

11:34.667 --> 11:36.458
You’re right, what does
that dog lady know anyway?

11:36.458 --> 11:38.000
I mean, Princess loves us!

11:38.000 --> 11:40.000
-Yeah!
-Right, Princess?

11:40.000 --> 11:42.208
Where’s Princess?

11:42.208 --> 11:44.000
-Oh, come on!
-Princess?

11:44.000 --> 11:45.792
MATT: Princess!

11:45.792 --> 11:47.375
Maybe we’re cat people.

11:47.375 --> 11:49.458
♪

11:49.458 --> 11:50.667
TIM: Uh-oh, what’s that?

11:50.667 --> 11:52.792
It’s your Valentine’s present.

11:52.792 --> 11:54.667
That’s my tattoo from last year.

11:54.667 --> 11:56.041
No, I added another heart.

11:56.041 --> 11:57.500
Mm, what is that, my lipstick?

11:57.500 --> 11:58.542
No, don’t smudge it!

12:00.875 --> 12:03.792
♪

12:03.792 --> 12:05.125
SOPHIA: Mom, Dad!

12:05.125 --> 12:06.917
I’m finally a woman!

12:06.917 --> 12:08.834
Guess what I got today?

12:08.834 --> 12:10.208
Already?

12:10.208 --> 12:12.834
Oh, no, it’s the hormones
in the chicken.

12:12.834 --> 12:14.333
A boyfriend!

12:14.333 --> 12:16.291
HEATHER: Ah,
you got a boyfriend?

12:16.291 --> 12:17.625
Well, what is his name?

12:17.625 --> 12:18.542
Pete.

12:18.542 --> 12:20.083
His last name
doesn’t matter ’cause

12:20.083 --> 12:22.333
-I’m not taking it anyway.
-Mm, yeah.

12:22.333 --> 12:24.667
Look what he got me
for Valentine’s Day!

12:24.667 --> 12:26.917
HEATHER: Oh, wow,
wow, wow, wow!

12:26.917 --> 12:29.375
He liked it, so he put
a necklace on it, huh?

12:29.375 --> 12:31.250
We’re not doin’
gifts here are we?

12:31.250 --> 12:32.500
Is Pete as funny as your Daddy?

12:32.500 --> 12:35.792
’Cause your Daddy
is pretty funny!

12:35.792 --> 12:39.083
-I feel like Anne Hathaway!
HEATHER: Mm, yeah.

12:39.083 --> 12:41.625
(phone ringing)

12:41.625 --> 12:42.542
Hello?

12:42.542 --> 12:44.375
Oh, hi, hi!

12:44.375 --> 12:46.583
It’s Pete’s mom.

12:46.583 --> 12:49.291
Are you calling
to plan the wedding?

12:49.291 --> 12:50.375
Okay, while your
Mom’s on the phone,

12:50.375 --> 12:52.208
let’s quickly pull together
a little dance routine

12:52.208 --> 12:53.834
and convince her that
it’s her present.

12:53.834 --> 12:54.834
You’re on your own.

12:54.834 --> 12:56.417
I’m still at the age
I can make a card,

12:56.417 --> 12:57.834
and she starts crying.

12:57.834 --> 12:59.333
HEATHER: So...

12:59.333 --> 13:01.250
Pete took that necklace
he gave Sophia

13:01.250 --> 13:03.166
from his mom’s jewelry box

13:03.166 --> 13:04.875
without asking.

13:04.875 --> 13:06.417
And...

13:06.417 --> 13:07.834
It’s real diamonds.

13:07.834 --> 13:10.834
My first boyfriend
and he’s rich?

13:10.834 --> 13:12.750
Maybe I will take his last name.

13:12.750 --> 13:14.000
Okay, sweetie,
well she’s gonna

13:14.000 --> 13:15.291
come over tomorrow
and pick it up,

13:15.291 --> 13:17.166
so why don’t you
run upstairs and get it?

13:17.166 --> 13:19.125
Wait, I have to give it back?

13:19.125 --> 13:20.375
Yeah, but don’t worry,
we’ll get you somethin’

13:20.375 --> 13:22.625
outta the claw machine.

13:22.625 --> 13:24.375
-Both of you.
HEATHER: Mm.

13:24.375 --> 13:25.500
♪

13:25.500 --> 13:26.667
SOPHIA: I lost it.

13:26.667 --> 13:28.500
You lost the necklace?

13:28.500 --> 13:29.959
Since this afternoon?

13:29.959 --> 13:32.667
You’re positive
that you lost it?

13:32.667 --> 13:34.375
I looked everywhere.

13:34.375 --> 13:35.667
No necklace.

13:35.667 --> 13:37.542
It’s like it just disappeared.

13:37.542 --> 13:40.542
I don’t think we can
rule out a black hole.

13:40.542 --> 13:42.750
Boy, you don’t need me
adding to your chaos.

13:42.750 --> 13:44.250
Can I go night swimming
at Carly’s house,

13:44.250 --> 13:45.542
and boys are going to be there?

13:45.542 --> 13:47.458
Yeah, honey, whatever.

13:47.458 --> 13:49.959
Listen, Sophia,
if you look me in the eye

13:49.959 --> 13:52.250
and you tell me that
you lost this necklace,

13:52.250 --> 13:54.417
okay, I’m gonna
believe you because

13:54.417 --> 13:56.208
in this family,

13:56.208 --> 13:57.917
we value honesty.

13:57.917 --> 13:59.750
That’s right,

13:59.750 --> 14:01.834
even more than material things.

14:01.834 --> 14:04.458
Yeah--

14:04.458 --> 14:06.834
I lost the necklace.

14:09.000 --> 14:09.917
Thank you.

14:09.917 --> 14:11.542
♪

14:11.542 --> 14:13.959
Wait, so she
lost it in one day?

14:13.959 --> 14:15.041
I know, I know, I know.

14:15.041 --> 14:16.500
I’m so sorry.

14:16.500 --> 14:19.709
I mean, we tore
the entire house apart.

14:19.709 --> 14:20.792
If I find it,

14:20.792 --> 14:22.917
obviously, I’ll call you.

14:22.917 --> 14:25.542
Yeah, I’m not buying it.

14:25.542 --> 14:26.750
You don’t believe me?

14:26.750 --> 14:28.250
Oh, no, I believe you.

14:28.250 --> 14:29.208
HEATHER: Listen,

14:29.208 --> 14:31.417
if Sophia says she lost it,

14:31.417 --> 14:33.083
then she lost it, okay?

14:33.083 --> 14:34.709
I trust my daughter.

14:34.709 --> 14:38.625
-Yeah, but all kids are liars.
-Oh, wow.

14:38.625 --> 14:39.792
Okay, you know what?

14:39.792 --> 14:41.417
I guess that I’m blessed.

14:41.417 --> 14:45.667
My family is built
on trust and honesty,

14:45.667 --> 14:47.625
and I’m sorry if yours isn’t.

14:47.625 --> 14:50.041
But the day that I
don’t believe my daughter

14:50.041 --> 14:52.250
is the day that we
stop being a family.

14:52.250 --> 14:59.208
♪

15:04.417 --> 15:07.166
I killed our family.

15:07.166 --> 15:09.250
TIM: Ah, it’s happening!
HEATHER: What?

15:09.250 --> 15:10.917
What, what?

15:10.917 --> 15:12.625
Oh, sweetie,
what’s the matter?

15:12.625 --> 15:15.750
I hid the necklace
so I could keep it.

15:15.750 --> 15:18.709
Now we have to stop
being a family.

15:18.709 --> 15:21.750
-What?
-I’m a monster!

15:21.750 --> 15:23.333
Just like Anne Hathaway.

15:23.333 --> 15:26.041
Oh, honey, no,
but why did you lie?

15:26.041 --> 15:28.000
It was the first
romantic present

15:28.000 --> 15:31.166
a boy has ever gotten me.

15:31.166 --> 15:32.333
Here.

15:32.333 --> 15:33.625
Take it.

15:33.625 --> 15:37.417
But, maybe put something
like it on my birthday list?

15:37.417 --> 15:41.291
I understand.
I mean, I get this completely.

15:41.291 --> 15:43.583
You know, presents make us feel

15:43.583 --> 15:47.250
loved and appreciated.

15:47.250 --> 15:48.417
But that doesn’t
make this right,

15:48.417 --> 15:49.667
and you have to return it,

15:49.667 --> 15:52.333
and you’re gonna have
to explain that you lied.

15:52.333 --> 15:54.000
I hate life lessons.

15:54.000 --> 15:56.583
Hey, we all make mistakes.

15:56.583 --> 15:58.792
And that is the true meaning

15:58.792 --> 16:00.250
of Valentine’s Day.

16:00.250 --> 16:01.750
♪

16:01.750 --> 16:02.750
HEATHER: Ugh, this is the worst.

16:02.750 --> 16:04.208
This is gonna be
more embarrassing

16:04.208 --> 16:05.750
than that time I drank
too much kombucha,

16:05.750 --> 16:08.000
and I shoplifted
from the grocery store.

16:11.834 --> 16:14.125
TABITHA: Coming!

16:14.125 --> 16:15.083
I think Sophia’s probably

16:15.083 --> 16:16.458
-learned her lesson.
-Yeah, I think so too.

16:16.458 --> 16:17.500
-You know what, let’s go.
TIM: Go!

16:17.500 --> 16:19.000
HEATHER: Let’s go.
SOPHIA: Woo!

16:19.000 --> 16:21.041
TIM: Go, go, go, go, go!

16:21.041 --> 16:22.333
♪

16:22.333 --> 16:24.542
Valentine’s Day is
a therapist’s busiest day,

16:24.542 --> 16:26.375
just like tax day
is for accountants,

16:26.375 --> 16:29.125
or the Fourth of July
is for finger surgeons.

16:32.083 --> 16:35.417
♪

16:35.417 --> 16:37.375
JOAN: I don’t know why
we’re having a picnic here,

16:37.375 --> 16:39.709
but I love you,
and that’s all that matters.

16:39.709 --> 16:42.041
Oh, no, no, no, no, Joanie.

16:42.041 --> 16:44.333
I want you to see something.

16:44.333 --> 16:45.333
Ta-da!

16:45.333 --> 16:46.500
♪

16:46.500 --> 16:48.500
JOAN: Just like our old one.

16:48.500 --> 16:52.166
Oh, I’ve missed this car!

16:52.166 --> 16:55.166
I regret ever having to sell it
when Heather was born,

16:55.166 --> 16:57.250
but you know,

16:57.250 --> 16:58.875
kids are about sacrifice

16:58.875 --> 17:01.834
and giving up everything
that’s important to you.

17:01.834 --> 17:03.834
Happy Valentine’s Day!

17:05.291 --> 17:06.375
You bought it?

17:06.375 --> 17:07.291
I’m about to,

17:07.291 --> 17:09.375
and then we’re gonna drive
up the coast in this baby,

17:09.375 --> 17:11.667
and have a romantic picnic,

17:11.667 --> 17:13.917
and make love in the backseat.

17:13.917 --> 17:16.125
Listen, you,
making love in the backseat

17:16.125 --> 17:18.625
was what led to us having
to get rid of this car

17:18.625 --> 17:21.000
in the first place.

17:21.000 --> 17:21.917
Oh, yeah, well,

17:21.917 --> 17:23.917
we can decide
where to do it later.

17:23.917 --> 17:26.875
Now watch me unleash
my negotiating magic.

17:26.875 --> 17:28.333
(phone ringing)

17:28.333 --> 17:30.083
That’s not a patient, is it?

17:30.083 --> 17:33.333
Yes, but Shelly’s gonna be fine.

17:33.333 --> 17:34.959
You’re going to be fine.

17:34.959 --> 17:37.083
GAVIN: Can I help you folks
find something today?

17:37.083 --> 17:40.458
Well, I’ll tell ya what you
can’t help me find is...

17:40.458 --> 17:43.125
this car here,
I’m not interested in this one.

17:43.125 --> 17:45.417
-John?
-No, no, honey,

17:45.417 --> 17:47.542
let the professionals
handle this.

17:47.542 --> 17:50.041
GAVIN: That car there
is actually not for sale.

17:50.041 --> 17:52.709
Oh, yeah, sure, dude.

17:52.709 --> 17:54.750
This guy’s come here
to play today.

17:54.750 --> 17:57.083
Nope, no games,
just not for sale.

17:57.083 --> 17:59.041
Is there another car
you’re interested in?

17:59.041 --> 18:01.250
Well, I’m interesting
in everything...

18:01.250 --> 18:02.542
but not this one.

18:02.542 --> 18:03.792
(phone ringing)

18:03.792 --> 18:05.000
JOAN: Oh, it’s Shelly again.

18:05.000 --> 18:07.166
She must really be struggling.

18:07.166 --> 18:08.417
Let me just explain to her

18:08.417 --> 18:10.250
that we’re impulse buying
our third car.

18:10.250 --> 18:12.417
She’ll understand.

18:12.417 --> 18:14.542
What about this one?

18:14.542 --> 18:16.250
Yeah, this one’s nice.

18:16.250 --> 18:19.709
Nicer than that one
over there that’s not for sale.

18:19.709 --> 18:21.917
Yeah, I’m just not so sure
about the price.

18:21.917 --> 18:24.750
Now, if that other car
over there was for sale,

18:24.750 --> 18:26.333
how much would that be?

18:26.333 --> 18:27.834
That car’s not for sale.

18:27.834 --> 18:29.625
I’ll give you $22,000.

18:29.625 --> 18:30.875
-Okay.
-Really?

18:30.875 --> 18:32.125
No, it’s not for sale.

18:32.125 --> 18:37.083
♪

18:37.083 --> 18:38.333
This guy’s good, Joanie.

18:38.333 --> 18:40.458
He keeps saying
it’s not for sale.

18:40.458 --> 18:43.208
But, maybe it’s not for sale.

18:43.208 --> 18:44.333
Well, it’s a good thing

18:44.333 --> 18:45.875
I’m doin’ this and not you.

18:45.875 --> 18:47.709
He’d eat you alive.

18:47.709 --> 18:50.125
GAVIN: So, you seem to
really like the Aston Martin.

18:50.125 --> 18:51.417
Why don’t we step into my office

18:51.417 --> 18:52.917
and run the numbers?

18:52.917 --> 18:55.166
Yeah, sure, why don’t we.

18:55.166 --> 18:56.542
GAVIN: You guys
want some coffee?

18:56.542 --> 18:57.667
JOHN: Sure.

18:57.667 --> 18:59.875
Yeah, now we’re makin’ money.

18:59.875 --> 19:02.333
Uh, I don’t really
want any coffee.

19:02.333 --> 19:03.291
That’s part of the game.

19:03.291 --> 19:05.208
Just get it,
and throw it in the trash.

19:05.208 --> 19:07.291
♪

19:07.291 --> 19:09.291
So, your paperwork is done.

19:09.291 --> 19:11.709
I just need your signature,

19:11.709 --> 19:14.125
and that red beauty is yours.

19:14.125 --> 19:16.083
So, uh,

19:16.083 --> 19:17.750
I’m just gonna
sign here then, huh?

19:17.750 --> 19:20.375
I’m, I’m really gonna do it!

19:20.375 --> 19:22.792
Here I go--I just
licked the pen.

19:22.792 --> 19:24.500
Yup, that’s what
we’ve been talkin’ about

19:24.500 --> 19:26.000
for the past hour...

19:26.000 --> 19:28.041
and you can keep that pen.

19:28.041 --> 19:29.709
Up again, honey.

19:29.709 --> 19:31.333
-John.
-So, I’m really gonna sign

19:31.333 --> 19:32.709
the paperwork, huh?

19:32.709 --> 19:33.959
Whenever you’re ready.

19:33.959 --> 19:39.542
♪

19:39.542 --> 19:41.583
Ah, you win!

19:41.583 --> 19:42.583
-Huh?
JOHN: All right,

19:42.583 --> 19:44.375
I don’t want to
buy an Aston Martin.

19:44.375 --> 19:45.625
I want the Chevelle,

19:45.625 --> 19:46.834
and I’ll pay anything!

19:46.834 --> 19:48.291
I won’t let you leave this lot

19:48.291 --> 19:50.208
until I’ve bought your car.

19:50.208 --> 19:52.417
I don’t think that’s
the right way to negotiate.

19:52.417 --> 19:53.458
Nah, I got this.

19:53.458 --> 19:55.250
No, no, name your price.

19:55.250 --> 19:56.208
I’ll double it!

19:56.208 --> 19:58.542
I’ll even throw in
the two coffees,

19:58.542 --> 20:00.750
and this new pen,

20:00.750 --> 20:02.834
and this gold stapler

20:02.834 --> 20:05.583
that I borrowed.

20:05.583 --> 20:07.250
Maybe he doesn’t
want to sell the car

20:07.250 --> 20:09.667
because it means
something to him.

20:09.667 --> 20:12.208
I don’t wanna talk about it.

20:12.208 --> 20:15.583
See, see you were wrong, Joanie.

20:15.583 --> 20:17.917
The car was my ex-wife’s.

20:17.917 --> 20:20.291
I should be over her by now,

20:20.291 --> 20:24.458
and I would sell it to you
if I was, but I’m not.

20:24.458 --> 20:27.250
John, could Gavin
and I have a word?

20:27.250 --> 20:30.333
No, he’s about to cave,
but okay.

20:30.333 --> 20:33.166
♪

20:35.917 --> 20:40.458
♪

20:40.458 --> 20:42.125
I’m ready to move on.

20:42.125 --> 20:44.500
I’ll give you
a great price on that car.

20:44.500 --> 20:47.375
Sounds like you’re gettin’
more than I am outta this deal.

20:47.375 --> 20:50.834
I’m not sure I’m interested
in a "great price."

20:50.834 --> 20:52.208
John.

20:52.208 --> 20:54.542
Leave this to
the professionals, hm?

20:54.542 --> 21:01.458
♪
